## Key concepts

| Concept | Role in the exploit |
|---|---|
| **Broken logic** | The password check always fails due to a compiler artifact â€” both branches lead to the failure path |
| **Buffer overflow** | `fgets` reads 100 bytes into a 64-byte stack buffer, overflowing past saved EBP/EIP |
| **Stack alignment** | `and $0xfffffff0, %esp` adds variable padding; the real offset (80) differs from the static calculation (72) |
| **ret2libc** | Overwrites EIP with `system()`, places `"/bin/sh"` as argument â€” no shellcode needed |
| **x86 calling convention** | After `ret`, the stack must contain: target address, return address, first argument |
| **Little-endian** | Addresses are written LSB-first: `0xf7e6aed0` â†’ `\xd0\xae\xe6\xf7` |
| **GDB** | Used to find `system`, `exit`, and `"/bin/sh"` addresses in libc at runtime |
